1
00:00:18,989 --> 00:00:22,459
Slow down for a minute,
will you, please, Jenkins?

2
00:01:15,509 --> 00:01:17,579
All right. Go ahead. Thank you.

3
00:01:38,149 --> 00:01:40,788
- Where are we, Jenkins?
- Fifth Avenue, sir.

4
00:01:40,949 --> 00:01:46,148
- I see that. But why are we here?
- This is your wedding anniversary.

5
00:01:46,309 --> 00:01:50,860
Oh, of course, of course, my 15th.
Delightful occasion.

6
00:01:51,029 --> 00:01:52,701
Thank you, Jenkins.

7
00:01:56,229 --> 00:01:59,027
- Good morning, Mr. Cortland.
- I'd like to get a bracelet.

8
00:01:59,189 --> 00:02:02,784
Diamond, of course. Here we are.

9
00:02:03,749 --> 00:02:09,665
Is this something like we have
in mind? Or perhaps this?

10
00:02:11,709 --> 00:02:14,223
Oh, that's beautiful.

11
00:02:14,429 --> 00:02:17,421
- I'll take that.
- Fine. That's my preference.

12
00:02:17,589 --> 00:02:19,068
Will there be anything else?

13
00:02:19,229 --> 00:02:24,587
No, thank you. Oh, yes, I wanna get
something for my wife too.

14
00:02:30,909 --> 00:02:32,581
- How much is this?
- Seven dollars.

15
00:02:32,749 --> 00:02:34,626
Will you put this in one
of your boxes?

16
00:02:34,789 --> 00:02:37,462
- Yes.
- Incidentally, what is it?

17
00:02:37,629 --> 00:02:42,020
- It's a Chinese backscratcher.
- Always wanted to have one of those.

18
00:02:42,189 --> 00:02:44,862
- Shall we send it, sir?
- No, I'll give it to her myself.

19
00:02:45,029 --> 00:02:47,463
- And about the bracelet, sir.
- I want that engraved.

20
00:02:47,629 --> 00:02:49,779
Yes, and to whom?

21
00:02:49,949 --> 00:02:53,783
To my dear, sweet...

22
00:02:56,629 --> 00:03:00,907
- May I use your telephone, please?
- Of course, right over there.

23
00:03:01,709 --> 00:03:04,269
I'll have her name for you
in just a minute.

24
00:03:07,389 --> 00:03:12,224
- The boss wants you on the phone.
- Thanks. I'm through with this table, Joe.

25
00:03:12,389 --> 00:03:15,142
Someone's still a beat off.

26
00:03:16,829 --> 00:03:20,504
- Hello, chief.
- What's the name of that pretty girl...

27
00:03:20,669 --> 00:03:24,059
...in the front line
of the modern group?

28
00:03:24,229 --> 00:03:28,108
The new one with
the dimples on her knee?

29
00:03:28,509 --> 00:03:32,343
Oh, Sheila Winthrop.
Yeah, that's right.

30
00:03:40,189 --> 00:03:43,226
- Miss Winthrop.
- Yes, Mr. Curtis.

31
00:03:43,389 --> 00:03:45,698
There's nothing I admire more
than independence...

32
00:03:45,869 --> 00:03:47,860
...but sometimes
it can be carried too far.

33
00:03:48,109 --> 00:03:51,499
Our group is known
for absolute precision.

34
00:03:51,669 --> 00:03:55,025
All the other girls are doing
this dance one way and you another.

35
00:03:55,189 --> 00:03:58,226
I'm sorry. But I don't know
that part of the routine.

36
00:03:58,429 --> 00:04:01,068
- Would you like to try it with me?
- I'd love to.

37
00:04:01,229 --> 00:04:03,824
Tommy, let's have the second 24 bars.
Ready? One and two and...

38
00:04:03,859 --> 00:04:06,419
Tommy, let's have the second 24 bars.
Ready? One and two and...

39
00:04:38,069 --> 00:04:41,061
- That's much better, thank you.
- Thank you.

40
00:04:41,429 --> 00:04:44,102
All right, now listen, kids.
I want the whole number.

41
00:04:44,269 --> 00:04:47,818
Places, please.
It's "Boogie Barcarolle," from the top.

42
00:04:47,989 --> 00:04:50,628
I'll do it with you. Are you ready?

43
00:04:51,109 --> 00:04:55,546
Music. Now, give me some
nice straight lines, please. Go.

44
00:06:35,069 --> 00:06:38,379
That's it. Take five minutes.

45
00:06:38,949 --> 00:06:40,701
Sheila.

46
00:06:41,109 --> 00:06:44,499
- Who do you think you're kidding?
- I don't know what you mean.

47
00:06:44,669 --> 00:06:48,105
- You know that dance routine.
- That's right.

48
00:06:48,269 --> 00:06:50,942
Then why do you muff it
when Mr. Curtis is around?

49
00:06:51,109 --> 00:06:53,828
- Because I like to dance with him.
- Is that all?

50
00:06:54,669 --> 00:06:56,944
- I like the way he talks.
- Is that all?

51
00:06:57,109 --> 00:06:59,464
- I like his personality.
- Is that all?

52
00:06:59,629 --> 00:07:03,508
- Isn't that enough?
- Don't get your hopes up, dear.

53
00:07:03,669 --> 00:07:06,183
- Why not?
- For eight hours a day, Mr. Curtis...

54
00:07:06,349 --> 00:07:09,580
...is up to his hips in pretty girls.
And we all look alike to him.

55
00:07:09,749 --> 00:07:12,661
- Really?
- Yes. To a hungry man, a lamb chop...

56
00:07:12,829 --> 00:07:16,583
...is a tasty dish. But to
the butcher, it's just a hunk of meat.

57
00:07:16,749 --> 00:07:19,263
Mr. Cortland wants to see you
in his office.

58
00:07:19,429 --> 00:07:22,341
- I take it all back, dear.
- Thank you, Mr. Curtis.

59
00:07:22,509 --> 00:07:24,803
- What do you take back, Marge?
- A remark I made about lamb chops.

60
00:07:24,838 --> 00:07:27,098
- What do you take back, Marge?
- A remark I made about lamb chops.

61
00:07:46,949 --> 00:07:48,098
Come in.

62
00:07:53,149 --> 00:07:56,539
- You sent for me, Mr. Cortland?
- Yes, I thought we might have a chat.

63
00:07:56,709 --> 00:07:58,825
- Won't you sit down, please?
- Thank you.

64
00:08:02,109 --> 00:08:05,704
- You know that I own this theatre?
- Yes, I do.

65
00:08:05,869 --> 00:08:07,939
Fine. Fine.

66
00:08:09,029 --> 00:08:12,783
- I took an interest in your work.
- Really?

67
00:08:12,989 --> 00:08:16,299
So much so that this morning
I was walking down Fifth Avenue...

68
00:08:16,469 --> 00:08:19,347
...I saw something rather beautiful
that reminded me of you.

69
00:08:19,509 --> 00:08:23,024
I wanted you to have it very much,
and so I bought it for you.

70
00:08:23,429 --> 00:08:26,387
This couldn't be a diamond bracelet,
could it?

71
00:08:26,549 --> 00:08:28,858
Yes, as a matter of fact, it's engraved.

72
00:08:29,029 --> 00:08:31,862
"To my dear, sweet Sheila."
Something I thought of.

73
00:08:32,029 --> 00:08:35,624
- How lovely.
- We do understand each other, don't we?

74
00:08:35,789 --> 00:08:37,780
- Yes, we do, don't we?
- Good.

75
00:08:40,189 --> 00:08:43,499
Now, I've got a little plan.

76
00:08:44,389 --> 00:08:45,822
I'm sorry.

77
00:08:48,029 --> 00:08:50,827
- Hello?
- Mrs. Cortland is on her way in.

78
00:08:51,029 --> 00:08:52,906
Thank you, Cummings.

79
00:08:53,709 --> 00:08:56,701
- I'm terribly sorry about this.
- I quite understand.

80
00:08:56,869 --> 00:08:58,780
Maybe this way would be better.

81
00:08:58,949 --> 00:09:01,668
- You are lovely, my dear.
- Thank you, Mr. Cortland.

82
00:09:01,829 --> 00:09:03,308
Oh, thank you, Miss Winthrop.

83
00:09:03,469 --> 00:09:05,778
We'll consider the proposition
closed then.

84
00:09:07,349 --> 00:09:10,705
I'm thinking of putting
her under long-term contract.

85
00:09:10,869 --> 00:09:14,418
She's an old friend of the family.
My family.

86
00:09:14,589 --> 00:09:17,387
Her father and my father, you know.
Like that:

87
00:09:18,269 --> 00:09:20,737
- She's beautiful, isn't she?
- Who?

88
00:09:20,909 --> 00:09:24,902
Oh, she? In a superficial sort of way.

89
00:09:26,949 --> 00:09:28,746
Will you stop looking at me like that?

90
00:09:28,909 --> 00:09:31,662
- Like what?
- You ought to know, you're doing it.

91
00:09:32,309 --> 00:09:35,142
Do we have to fight
on our wedding anniversary?

92
00:09:35,309 --> 00:09:39,143
- How did you happen to remember that?
- Well, Jenkins told me.

93
00:09:39,309 --> 00:09:40,583
Very thoughtful of Jenkins.

94
00:09:40,709 --> 00:09:43,177
I was thoughtful too.
I bought you a present.

95
00:09:43,349 --> 00:09:46,864
It's in my coat pocket, if you
wanna go and look for it.

96
00:09:58,789 --> 00:10:03,340
Oh. Oh, it's lovely, Martin.

97
00:10:03,549 --> 00:10:06,461
- Interesting gadget, isn't it?
- Gadget?

98
00:10:06,629 --> 00:10:09,939
- Yes, it's to scratch your back.
- Scratch your back?

99
00:10:10,109 --> 00:10:13,545
Yes, it's Chinese. You scratch it up
and down and crosswise.

100
00:10:13,709 --> 00:10:15,586
What on earth are you talking about?

101
00:10:15,749 --> 00:10:18,582
Oh, wait a minute,
I'll show you how it works.

102
00:10:19,909 --> 00:10:23,788
- Where did you get that?
- Out of your pocket.

103
00:10:23,949 --> 00:10:27,942
- My dear, there has been a mistake.
- I see. Who is "dear, sweet Sheila"?

104
00:10:28,109 --> 00:10:30,782
The girl that just went out.
Don't jump to conclusions.

105
00:10:30,949 --> 00:10:33,668
No, no, I won't.
We'll take it nice and easy.

106
00:10:33,829 --> 00:10:35,342
But, Julia, you do not understand.

107
00:10:35,509 --> 00:10:38,228
No, I know I don't, dear.
But I will when you explain.

108
00:10:38,389 --> 00:10:42,780
- I bought that for Robert Curtis.
- Should look lovely on him.

109
00:10:42,989 --> 00:10:45,901
Don't be ridiculous.
Robert is crazy about Miss Winthrop.

110
00:10:46,069 --> 00:10:50,824
He asked me to pick a present out
for her. So I did. See?

111
00:10:51,029 --> 00:10:54,738
I'm disappointed in you. There was
a time when your alibis were gems.

112
00:10:54,949 --> 00:10:58,385
- Remember the Russian dancer?
- She was Portuguese.

113
00:10:58,549 --> 00:11:01,780
Before you talked your way out of that,
you rewrote the Arabian Nights.

114
00:11:01,909 --> 00:11:03,501
Now you've lost your imagination.

115
00:11:03,629 --> 00:11:05,381
I'm getting bored with you.

116
00:11:05,549 --> 00:11:09,383
Bored? Is it my fault you reached
into the wrong pocket?

117
00:11:09,549 --> 00:11:13,667
You started the whole thing. That's
the trouble around here, no privacy.

118
00:11:13,829 --> 00:11:16,787
People reaching into wrong pockets.
No organization.

119
00:11:16,949 --> 00:11:18,667
How's a man to run a theatre?

120
00:11:18,829 --> 00:11:21,821
- Is this what you intended for me?
- Yes.

121
00:11:21,989 --> 00:11:25,220
As a matter of fact, you know,
that's quite a collector's item.

122
00:11:25,389 --> 00:11:28,745
Ming dynasty.
But it also has its practical side.

123
00:11:28,909 --> 00:11:31,423
You can scratch yourself
in all sorts of places.

124
00:11:31,589 --> 00:11:32,624
I imagine.

125
00:11:32,789 --> 00:11:37,101
Oh, you're very thoughtful, Martin.
I'm sure Miss Winthrop will agree.

126
00:11:37,269 --> 00:11:38,497
You don't believe me then?

127
00:11:38,669 --> 00:11:41,581
Oh, of course I do.
But that's because I know you so well.

128
00:11:41,749 --> 00:11:45,708
I'm just wondering how your story
will sound to 12 strange men.

129
00:11:46,829 --> 00:11:51,664
Twelve strange men.
Twelve strange men. She's batty.

130
00:11:52,589 --> 00:11:58,425
What's 12 strange men got to do
with this? Football team, 11 men.

131
00:11:58,589 --> 00:12:01,422
A baseball team, nine.

132
00:12:01,829 --> 00:12:06,186
Symphony orchestra, 100 men.

133
00:12:06,349 --> 00:12:08,658
Twelve men.

134
00:12:12,029 --> 00:12:14,623
A jury!

135
00:12:16,989 --> 00:12:21,028
Robert, prepare yourself for a shock.
Julia's going to divorce me.

136
00:12:21,229 --> 00:12:23,982
- I'll be first to congratulate her.
- How can you say that?

137
00:12:24,149 --> 00:12:27,459
You know I don't want a divorce.
I'm happily married. I love my wife.

138
00:12:27,629 --> 00:12:29,904
And besides,
all this property is in her name.

139
00:12:30,069 --> 00:12:32,583
She's gonna strip me right down
to my underwear too.

140
00:12:32,749 --> 00:12:35,217
You ought to think of that
before you gallop after...

141
00:12:35,429 --> 00:12:38,307
...something you can't catch.
Who is it this time?

142
00:12:38,469 --> 00:12:42,382
Sheila Winthrop. I bought her this,
and my wife found it in my pocket.

143
00:12:42,549 --> 00:12:44,779
I imagine you had a good reason
for buying that.

144
00:12:44,949 --> 00:12:47,383
- I certainly did. We're good friends.
- Oh, I see.

145
00:12:47,549 --> 00:12:50,268
- Besides, it's none of your business.
- I agree with you.

146
00:12:50,469 --> 00:12:54,781
- Wait, you're in this too, you know.
- Me? What have I to do with it?

147
00:12:54,949 --> 00:12:58,544
I told Julia you bought this for Sheila
and that you were in love with her.

148
00:12:58,709 --> 00:13:01,860
Oh, you did, did you?
I'm going to tell her differently.

149
00:13:02,029 --> 00:13:04,259
You don't have to.
She doesn't believe it anyway.

150
00:13:04,469 --> 00:13:05,948
Please, you've got to help me.

151
00:13:06,109 --> 00:13:08,828
If you get me out of this jam,
it'll never happen again.

152
00:13:08,989 --> 00:13:12,140
No more galloping, I swear it.
Please, Robert?

153
00:13:12,309 --> 00:13:15,540
- All right, what do you want me to do?
- Well, it's very simple.

154
00:13:15,709 --> 00:13:18,746
I'll take Julia to the Crystal Roof
for our anniversary dinner.

155
00:13:18,909 --> 00:13:23,027
You bring Sheila and prove to my wife
that you are in love with Sheila.

156
00:13:23,189 --> 00:13:25,862
What? Well, what would Sheila think?

157
00:13:26,029 --> 00:13:28,702
Make her believe it too.
If she doesn't, Julia won't.

158
00:13:28,869 --> 00:13:31,781
That won't be difficult.
She has a friendly disposition.

159
00:13:31,949 --> 00:13:34,986
Turn on the old charm, you know.
Fascinate her.

160
00:13:35,149 --> 00:13:37,379
Do anything so long as you
make my wife...

161
00:13:37,549 --> 00:13:40,017
...believe I was telling the truth
when I lied to her.

162
00:13:40,189 --> 00:13:41,224
Is that all?

163
00:13:41,389 --> 00:13:45,860
If you get a chance, you might put in
a good word for me with Sheila.

164
00:14:03,509 --> 00:14:05,420
Hello.

165
00:14:05,549 --> 00:14:07,187
I said, hello.

166
00:14:07,309 --> 00:14:09,504
Oh, hello.

167
00:14:10,789 --> 00:14:13,826
I'm sorry. For a minute,
I was a long way off.

168
00:14:13,989 --> 00:14:16,025
- Have a nice trip?
- Wonderful.

169
00:14:16,189 --> 00:14:21,422
I'm glad you came back.
Incidentally, you dance beautifully.

170
00:14:21,589 --> 00:14:24,979
- You didn't think so at rehearsal.
- Oh, that.

171
00:14:25,149 --> 00:14:29,108
Confidentially, Sheila, I'm delighted
every time you make a mistake.

172
00:14:29,269 --> 00:14:30,987
I get a chance to dance with you.

173
00:14:31,149 --> 00:14:35,347
Confidentially, I make mistakes
for the same reason.

174
00:14:37,349 --> 00:14:39,419
Good evening, Mr. Cortland.

175
00:14:41,229 --> 00:14:42,867
What are you looking for?

176
00:14:43,029 --> 00:14:45,702
Me? Nothing.
Why should I be looking for anything?

177
00:15:03,589 --> 00:15:06,149
- Thanks, Sheila. It was lovely.
- That's your fault.

178
00:15:06,509 --> 00:15:08,147
Look! There are Robert and Sheila.

179
00:15:08,309 --> 00:15:10,539
- Oh, how surprising.
- Let's go over and say hello.

180
00:15:10,709 --> 00:15:13,177
Just to be polite.
Just for a minute.

181
00:15:13,349 --> 00:15:16,546
- Oh, Robert.
- Hello, Martin. Hello, Julia.

182
00:15:16,709 --> 00:15:18,540
- Well, this is a surprise.
- Is it?

183
00:15:18,709 --> 00:15:20,301
- Of course it is.
- Want to sit down?

184
00:15:20,469 --> 00:15:23,461
Thank you. That's nice of you.
We have a table over here.

185
00:15:23,629 --> 00:15:27,668
Way back is the best we could get.
I hope we're not gonna crowd you.

186
00:15:27,829 --> 00:15:30,263
Sheila, how rude of me.
You know Miss Winthrop, Julia?

187
00:15:30,429 --> 00:15:33,262
- Yes. How do you do, Miss Winthrop?
- How do you do?

188
00:15:33,469 --> 00:15:35,903
It was outside of my husband's office,
wasn't it?

189
00:15:36,389 --> 00:15:40,667
I'm glad you both dropped by.
I was just about to...

190
00:15:40,829 --> 00:15:42,467
- You first, Robert.
- Thank you.

191
00:15:42,629 --> 00:15:44,699
I was gonna say,
I'm glad you both dropped by.

192
00:15:44,869 --> 00:15:47,099
It makes a very pleasant occasion
even more so.

193
00:15:47,309 --> 00:15:50,187
Yes, doesn't it? And it's our
15th wedding anniversary too.

194
00:15:50,349 --> 00:15:52,226
- Congratulations.
- Thank you.

195
00:15:52,389 --> 00:15:55,347
Robert, did you happen to see
the lovely present Martin gave me?

196
00:15:55,549 --> 00:15:59,178
- It was a backscratcher, Chinese.
- Ming dynasty. Ming.

197
00:15:59,349 --> 00:16:02,944
When we were first married, it was
orchids. Now it's a backscratcher.

198
00:16:03,109 --> 00:16:06,499
Try and scratch your back
with an orchid, I always say.

199
00:16:06,669 --> 00:16:09,103
It seems to be a special occasion
for both of us.

200
00:16:09,269 --> 00:16:12,261
How did you like your present,
my dear?

201
00:16:12,709 --> 00:16:14,381
What present do you mean?

202
00:16:15,269 --> 00:16:17,464
That's a funny thing about orchids.

203
00:16:17,629 --> 00:16:21,463
I was talking to a guy the other day
who breeds... Raises orchids.

204
00:16:21,629 --> 00:16:23,142
He said he couldn't do...

205
00:16:23,349 --> 00:16:27,627
You gotta make so much difference
about the yellow ones. But...

206
00:16:27,789 --> 00:16:30,542
Martin, what in the world
are you doing?

207
00:16:31,109 --> 00:16:34,658
- I'm tying my shoe.
- Try doing it with both hands.

208
00:16:35,589 --> 00:16:39,377
- Well, what were we talking about?
- The present Robert gave Miss Winthrop.

209
00:16:39,589 --> 00:16:41,466
Julia, can't you keep a secret?

210
00:16:41,629 --> 00:16:45,622
I was saving this as a surprise,
but now that you know it...

211
00:16:45,789 --> 00:16:47,347
...I hope you like it.

212
00:16:50,309 --> 00:16:53,699
- This couldn't be a diamond bracelet?
- Open it.

213
00:17:00,149 --> 00:17:02,299
"To my dear, sweet Sheila."

214
00:17:03,229 --> 00:17:06,778
The funny thing was that when my wife
found that in my pocket...

215
00:17:06,949 --> 00:17:09,827
...she thought that I was the one
who bought it for you.

216
00:17:11,989 --> 00:17:14,184
How could you possibly think
such a thing?

217
00:17:14,389 --> 00:17:16,300
Because I know Martin.

218
00:17:16,509 --> 00:17:18,704
Do you like it, Sheila?

219
00:17:19,349 --> 00:17:24,742
Like it? It's wonderful. It's the most
gorgeous thing I ever saw!

220
00:17:27,829 --> 00:17:30,627
Now what do you think,
Miss Susie Suspicious?

221
00:17:30,789 --> 00:17:31,904
Ask me later.

222
00:17:32,109 --> 00:17:36,182
Oh, Mr. Curtis, this is the nicest thing
that ever happened to me.

223
00:17:37,629 --> 00:17:41,099
