00:53:21,389 --> 00:53:24,426
Now, what's your real idea
in doing this show in camp?

681
00:53:24,589 --> 00:53:25,942
Why, I'm surprised at you.

682
00:53:26,109 --> 00:53:28,987
You know I've always wanted
to do something for the government.

683
00:53:29,149 --> 00:53:31,344
You'd think I was getting
something out of this.

684
00:53:31,509 --> 00:53:34,387
- Only my services for nothing.
- What do you mean, for nothing?

685
00:53:34,549 --> 00:53:36,460
The government pays you $21 a month.

686
00:53:36,629 --> 00:53:40,144
Where does that money come from?
The taxpayers. I'm a taxpayer.

687
00:53:40,309 --> 00:53:42,539
- Let me thank you, Martin.
- Don't mention it.

688
00:53:42,709 --> 00:53:46,304
If I didn't hate that guardhouse so much,
I wouldn't even be talking to you.

689
00:53:49,389 --> 00:53:51,778
What are they for,
to keep you from swiping medals?

690
00:53:51,949 --> 00:53:53,587
Part of my deal with the government.

691
00:53:53,709 --> 00:53:55,620
They wouldn't let you out
except under guard.

692
00:53:55,749 --> 00:53:58,388
Every time you get an idea,
something happens to me.

693
00:53:58,549 --> 00:54:00,619
All right. I'm your man.
The show is on.

694
00:54:00,789 --> 00:54:04,498
I'll tell you why. Next door lives a little
lady who's going to dance with me.

695
00:54:04,669 --> 00:54:06,785
- Little lady? Who?
- Miss Sheila Winthrop.

696
00:54:06,949 --> 00:54:09,907
Sheila Winthrop? Up here?
Robert, you don't want her.

697
00:54:10,069 --> 00:54:14,108
Why, she's a dangerous character.
She almost broke me up with my wife.

698
00:54:14,269 --> 00:54:17,705
Besides, I promised the part
to somebody else.

699
00:54:17,869 --> 00:54:19,188
Now it comes out.

700
00:54:19,349 --> 00:54:22,227
I thought I recognized that look
in your eye. Who is it now?

701
00:54:22,389 --> 00:54:26,382
Well, she's a very nice little item
named Sonya. A gorgeous creature.

702
00:54:26,549 --> 00:54:27,982
I've given her my word...

703
00:54:28,149 --> 00:54:31,505
Give her a bracelet instead,
because Sonya isn't dancing in this show.

704
00:54:31,669 --> 00:54:32,758
Robert, my pal...

705
00:54:32,829 --> 00:54:35,389
You promised there'd be
no more galloping over rooftops.

706
00:54:35,549 --> 00:54:37,221
This is different.
She's a foreigner.

707
00:54:37,389 --> 00:54:40,825
What's different?
A gallop is a gallop in any language.

708
00:54:41,629 --> 00:54:44,097
Hey! This way.

709
00:54:51,869 --> 00:54:55,828
Hey, sergeant, bring me in a house,
will you? Right here. Put it here.

710
00:54:55,989 --> 00:54:59,299
And I want a tree right here.

711
00:54:59,469 --> 00:55:00,504
That's right.

712
00:55:00,669 --> 00:55:02,227
Let me see, now...

713
00:55:02,469 --> 00:55:05,108
Hey, boys! Bring in the ocean, will you?

714
00:55:05,509 --> 00:55:07,784
That's right. Come on!

715
00:55:08,189 --> 00:55:12,705
- Okay. Sergeant, is Miss Winthrop ready?
- Yes, she's ready.

716
00:55:13,909 --> 00:55:19,541
That Miss Winthrop, she is so beautiful,
and I hate her so much!

717
00:55:19,709 --> 00:55:21,586
When will Mr. Curtis put me in her place?

718
00:55:21,749 --> 00:55:24,627
Any day, Sonya.
I'm working on a new angle.

719
00:55:24,789 --> 00:55:27,622
A new angle, old angle,
this angle, that angle.

720
00:55:27,789 --> 00:55:30,462
I want to dance,
and all you do is "angle" me.

721
00:55:30,629 --> 00:55:33,143
- Now, listen, you trust me, don't you?
- No.

722
00:55:33,309 --> 00:55:36,107
Well, that's ridiculous.
Everybody trusts me.

723
00:55:37,709 --> 00:55:43,261
My dear, I've a feeling you are

724
00:55:43,389 --> 00:55:48,702
So near and yet so far

725
00:55:48,829 --> 00:55:54,825
You appear lik e a radiant star

726
00:55:54,949 --> 00:56:00,546
First so near
Then again so far

727
00:56:00,669 --> 00:56:05,789
I just start getting you k een on
Clinches galore with me

728
00:56:06,669 --> 00:56:12,380
When fate steps in on the scene
And mops up the floor with me

729
00:56:12,509 --> 00:56:17,822
No wonder I'm a bit under par

730
00:56:17,949 --> 00:56:23,626
For you're so near
And yet so far

731
00:56:23,749 --> 00:56:29,858
My condition is only so-so
'Cause whenever I feel you're close, oh

732
00:56:29,989 --> 00:56:32,867
You turn out to be

733
00:56:32,989 --> 00:56:36,504
Oh, so far

734
00:59:26,469 --> 00:59:29,666
- Sheila, you're wonderful.
- That's because you're a good teacher.

735
00:59:29,829 --> 00:59:32,901
What's wonderful about you
isn't anything I taught you.

736
00:59:33,069 --> 00:59:35,424
What's wonderful about you is you.

737
00:59:35,589 --> 00:59:36,817
That's bracelet talk.

738
00:59:36,989 --> 00:59:39,219
Sure it is, but not the way
you think it is.

739
00:59:39,389 --> 00:59:43,428
That bracelet happens to mean
an awful lot to me. It brought us together.

740
00:59:43,589 --> 00:59:46,228
Well, that's one way of looking at it.

741
00:59:46,389 --> 00:59:48,778
That's the way I look at it.
I bought it from Martin.

742
00:59:50,349 --> 00:59:51,782
You did?

743
00:59:55,509 --> 00:59:58,899
Robert, you're one of the most
charming men I've ever known.

744
00:59:59,069 --> 01:00:01,663
And the most unconvincing.

745
01:00:04,549 --> 01:00:08,588
Oh, Captain Curtis,
are we too late to see the rehearsals?

746
01:00:08,749 --> 01:00:10,819
No, we're starting again
in a few moments.

747
01:00:10,989 --> 01:00:13,867
I'd like to speak to Sheila
if you can spare her.

748
01:00:14,029 --> 01:00:16,099
Yes, sir. Of course.
For a few minutes.

749
01:00:16,269 --> 01:00:20,342
- I have something to tell her.
- Tom is being transferred to Panama.

750
01:00:21,149 --> 01:00:23,424
Come on, Sheila.
I'll tell you all about it.

751
01:00:23,589 --> 01:00:29,221
Isn't it wonderful? After all these years,
they're going to be married.

752
01:00:29,389 --> 01:00:30,742
What?

753
01:00:30,909 --> 01:00:33,787
- I didn't know a thing about it.
- He's going to ask her now.

754
01:00:33,949 --> 01:00:36,258
- Do you think she might say yes?
- Of course.

755
01:00:36,429 --> 01:00:41,264
Our family's been planning it for years.
Don't look so upset, Capt. Curtis.

756
01:00:41,429 --> 01:00:44,739
They won't be leaving for Panama
until after your show is over.

757
01:00:44,909 --> 01:00:47,343
Pardon me, please.
I have to change my clothes.

758
01:00:47,509 --> 01:00:49,340
Oh, Robert?
Wait a minute, please.

759
01:00:49,509 --> 01:00:53,024
One more chance to save my wife
from a terrible fate. Sonya's threatening...

760
01:00:53,189 --> 01:00:55,578
You're wasting your breath.
Where's that bracelet?

761
01:00:55,749 --> 01:00:59,901
It's in your apartment, in my suitcase.
Sonya is... Where are you going?

762
01:01:00,069 --> 01:01:04,187
To my apartment. Say one more word,
and I'll throw those bloodhounds at you.

763
01:01:10,909 --> 01:01:13,548
To the apartment.
After all I've done for him.

764
01:01:13,709 --> 01:01:15,062
After all these...

765
01:01:15,269 --> 01:01:17,942
Hey, I changed the name
on the bracelet!

766
01:01:20,869 --> 01:01:24,418
Say, that's fine. I'm a genius!

767
01:01:25,029 --> 01:01:28,066
I'll bring them together again,
and your conscience will be clear.

768
01:01:28,229 --> 01:01:31,665
But I don't worry about my conscience.
I only worry about my career.

769
01:01:31,829 --> 01:01:33,899
You let me do the worrying, huh?

770
01:01:34,069 --> 01:01:38,347
All right. I let you do the worrying,
but if your plan doesn't work...

771
01:01:38,509 --> 01:01:41,899
Oh, it will work, believe me.
I wouldn't be mixed up in a thing like this.

772
01:01:42,069 --> 01:01:46,426
It's pretty low, you know.
But it's a national emergency, my dear.

773
01:01:48,069 --> 01:01:49,263
Well, Sheila?

774
01:01:49,429 --> 01:01:52,865
- Aunt Louise, Tom proposed to me.
- Yes.

775
01:01:53,389 --> 01:01:58,224
And out of the clear sky,
I realized I was in love with Robert.

776
01:01:58,389 --> 01:01:59,424
Did you tell Tom?

777
01:01:59,709 --> 01:02:02,906
Not yet. Tom asked me not to give him
my answer until tonight.

778
01:02:03,069 --> 01:02:06,857
What an eventful day this is.
When did Robert ask you to marry him?

779
01:02:07,029 --> 01:02:09,020
He hasn't yet...

780
01:02:09,229 --> 01:02:10,582
...but I think he will.

781
01:02:10,749 --> 01:02:13,946
I suspected something like that.
I've been married three times.

782
01:02:14,109 --> 01:02:15,383
- Four.
- That's right.

783
01:02:15,549 --> 01:02:17,460
I keep forgetting poor Mr. Trapscott.

784
01:02:18,789 --> 01:02:19,878
How do you do?

785
01:02:19,949 --> 01:02:21,826
You seem familiar with Army regulations.

786
01:02:21,989 --> 01:02:24,059
What happens to a private
who goes AWOL?

787
01:02:24,229 --> 01:02:27,665
- Well, it depends. Why?
- I'm afraid Robert's in quite a jam.

788
01:02:27,829 --> 01:02:31,219
He's in his apartment in town,
and Col. Shiller is due in half an hour.

789
01:02:31,389 --> 01:02:33,619
- Why don't you phone?
- I have. He doesn't answer.

790
01:02:33,789 --> 01:02:36,986
If anything happens to that boy,
I'll never forgive myself.

791
01:02:38,869 --> 01:02:40,780
I'll go get him. My car's right outside.

792
01:02:40,949 --> 01:02:43,065
- It won't be too much trouble?
- Not at all.

793
01:02:43,229 --> 01:02:45,220
There's something
I want to talk over with him.

794
01:02:45,389 --> 01:02:47,459
You've taken the load off my mind.

795
01:02:47,669 --> 01:02:49,068
- See you later.
- Bye, dear.

796
01:02:49,229 --> 01:02:51,424
- Will you pardon me, please?
- All right.

797
01:02:53,629 --> 01:02:54,964
Martin, aren't you ashamed?

798
01:02:54,999 --> 01:02:56,300
Martin, aren't you ashamed?

799
01:02:57,109 --> 01:03:00,260
Can you forget those gophers
long enough to do me a favour?

800
01:03:00,429 --> 01:03:01,464
Sure. What's up?

801
01:03:01,629 --> 01:03:05,065
Listen, I've got to go AWOL long enough
to get a wedding license.

802
01:03:05,229 --> 01:03:07,823
I've got to convince her I'm on the level
when I propose.

803
01:03:07,989 --> 01:03:09,388
- Miss Winthrop?
- Yeah.

804
01:03:09,549 --> 01:03:13,258
I want you to keep those guards so busy
they won't miss me for an hour or so.

805
01:03:13,429 --> 01:03:16,819
By the time you change your clothes,
we'll have everything under control.

806
01:03:16,989 --> 01:03:19,105
Okay, fellas. So long, fellas.

807
01:03:39,149 --> 01:03:40,867
Hi, soldier.

808
01:04:04,869 --> 01:04:07,337
Hey, fellas, did a hat go by here?

809
01:04:07,509 --> 01:04:09,465
Hey, Kewpie! Kewpie!

810
01:04:09,629 --> 01:04:13,065
Where are you? Kewpie!
I got him.

811
01:04:13,389 --> 01:04:15,220
Kewpie! Here it is.

812
01:04:15,389 --> 01:04:18,301
Boy, are we lucky! If he'd got away,
goodbye, Camp Weston.

813
01:04:18,469 --> 01:04:20,460
- What's going on?
- We got a spy under there.

814
01:04:20,629 --> 01:04:23,746
- A what?
- It's a foreign pigeon from Europe.

815
01:04:23,909 --> 01:04:25,740
- What'll you do?
- We gotta get the major.

816
01:04:25,909 --> 01:04:27,786
Keep your eyes on it.
Don't let it get away!

817
01:04:27,949 --> 01:04:29,905
Wait a minute.
How can a pigeon be a spy?

818
01:04:30,069 --> 01:04:32,708
They train them.
They import a trainer from the Army.

819
01:04:32,869 --> 01:04:36,748
It's got a camera tied to its leg.
We caught it taking pictures of the camp.

820
01:04:36,909 --> 01:04:40,822
- Well, I'm a son of a gun.
- Hey! Don't do that.

821
01:04:40,989 --> 01:04:43,457
If that bird ever... You'd both be shot.

822
01:04:43,629 --> 01:04:46,939
Don't let that pigeon get away from you,
soldier. Come on, Swivel.

823
01:04:55,749 --> 01:04:58,547
- What's going on here?
- Something's under the hat.

824
01:04:58,709 --> 01:05:00,347
- What is it, boys?
- It's a spy.

825
01:05:00,509 --> 01:05:02,864
- In the hat.
- In whose hat? Are you crazy?

826
01:05:03,029 --> 01:05:04,940
It's a pigeon spy. European.

827
01:05:05,109 --> 01:05:08,658
It's a spy, all right.
He's got a camera strapped to his leg.

828
01:05:08,829 --> 01:05:12,299
Whoever heard of a pigeon
that could operate a camera?

829
01:05:12,749 --> 01:05:14,979
The son of a gun bit me!

830
01:05:30,469 --> 01:05:32,778
Oh, Mr. Curtis. You frightened me!

831
01:05:32,949 --> 01:05:34,587
What do you think you did to me?

832
01:05:34,749 --> 01:05:36,262
What are you doing here?

833
01:05:36,429 --> 01:05:38,579
This happens to be my apartment.

834
01:05:39,029 --> 01:05:43,341
I'm sorry. I didn't know.
Mr. Cortland told me I could use it.

835
01:05:43,509 --> 01:05:46,421
Well, now, that's mighty chummy
all around, isn't it?

836
01:05:47,509 --> 01:05:50,706
My, this is terrible!
What would people think?

837
01:05:50,869 --> 01:05:54,305
Take it easy, my innocent little friend.
I'll be out of here in one minute.

838
01:05:54,469 --> 01:05:58,462
Tell Mr. Cortland the next time he passes
out apartments that don't belong to him...

839
01:06:00,029 --> 01:06:01,587
The bloodhounds.

840
01:06:11,229 --> 01:06:13,345
Robert, are you there?

841
01:06:15,509 --> 01:06:18,581
Why, Sheila!
Lmagine you standing there.

842
01:06:21,069 --> 01:06:22,821
Why, yes, it's Sheila.

843
01:06:22,989 --> 01:06:25,787
You might let me in.
I'm not selling anything.

844
01:06:27,709 --> 01:06:30,177
Sure, sure. Come in.

845
01:06:30,349 --> 01:06:34,706
- Well, Sheila, how are you?
- I'm fine, but you're in trouble.

846
01:06:34,869 --> 01:06:38,225
- What trouble did you hear about?
- You're AWOL. They're looking for you.

847
01:06:38,389 --> 01:06:40,425
As trouble goes, that's nothing.

848
01:06:40,589 --> 01:06:43,581
If you go back to the guardhouse,
that's a lot of trouble to me.

849
01:06:43,749 --> 01:06:45,467
Sheila, that's sweet.

850
01:06:45,629 --> 01:06:47,859
Come on, I'll drive you back in my car.

851
01:06:49,749 --> 01:06:51,660
That must be the boys.

852
01:06:51,949 --> 01:06:53,985
Better let me handle this.

853
01:06:56,509 --> 01:06:59,307
Hello, Miss Winthrop.
Is Pvt. Curtis in there?

854
01:06:59,469 --> 01:07:01,346
I thought he was in the Army.

855
01:07:01,509 --> 01:07:04,103
He'll be in the Army plenty
when we nab him.

856
01:07:04,269 --> 01:07:07,625
Well, there's no hurry.
We'll wait around a while.

857
01:07:10,469 --> 01:07:12,585
- Is there a back way out?
- Back way?

858
01:07:12,749 --> 01:07:14,819
This is a second floor apartment.
Oh, wait!

859
01:07:14,989 --> 01:07:17,583
There's a fire escape
outside the bedroom window.

860
01:07:18,109 --> 01:07:21,465
- Hold it! We can't go in there.
- Why not?

861
01:07:21,629 --> 01:07:23,824
Well, you see, that's my bedroom.

862
01:07:23,989 --> 01:07:25,502
Don't be coy.

863
01:07:25,669 --> 01:07:27,739
Well, I mean, there's work
going on in there.

864
01:07:27,909 --> 01:07:30,059
There's a plumber.

865
01:07:30,229 --> 01:07:33,585
- What difference does that make?
- What difference?

866
01:07:35,069 --> 01:07:38,982
- There you are.
- He's just fixing the shower. Come on.

867
01:07:49,469 --> 01:07:51,027
Charming, wasn't it?

868
01:07:52,749 --> 01:07:56,105
- You mean, that little...
- That dainty little garment. Yes.

869
01:07:56,269 --> 01:07:59,147
What the well-dressed plumber
is wearing, I guess.

870
01:07:59,309 --> 01:08:02,585
It takes all kinds of plumbers
to make a world.

871
01:08:02,749 --> 01:08:06,185
It was simply adorable.
I'd love to know where he bought it.

872
01:08:06,349 --> 01:08:10,183
No, I wouldn't do that. You don't know
how some people feel about those things.

873
01:08:10,349 --> 01:08:12,260
Plumber?

874
01:08:12,909 --> 01:08:14,900
His voice is changing.

875
01:08:15,069 --> 01:08:16,900
Sonya, come out of there.

876
01:08:20,789 --> 01:08:23,587
Tell Miss Winthrop
exactly what happened.

877
01:08:23,749 --> 01:08:27,947
- Shall I tell her everything?
- Yes. What do you mean, everything?

878
01:08:28,109 --> 01:08:30,703
- Don't you believe it, Sheila.
- I don't.

879
01:08:30,869 --> 01:08:33,144
Sonya is trying too hard.

880
01:08:33,309 --> 01:08:36,142
- Sheila, you're wonderful.
- I'm surprised, Sonya.

881
01:08:36,309 --> 01:08:39,506
- This is the oldest game in the world.
- You think so?

882
01:08:39,669 --> 01:08:42,706
If I were you,
I'd stick to plumbing exclusively.

883
01:08:44,709 --> 01:08:47,621
A plumber? Aren't you silly?
Why didn't you tell me the truth?

884
01:08:47,789 --> 01:08:50,098
How did I know you were
one girl in 50 million?

885
01:08:50,269 --> 01:08:53,261
Let this be a lesson to you.
Let's get down this fire escape.

886
01:08:53,909 --> 01:08:56,787
By the way, what did you come
to your apartment for?

887
01:08:58,469 --> 01:09:00,744
- It was a surprise, Sheila.
- For whom?

888
01:09:00,909 --> 01:09:03,218
- You.
- Tell me.

889
01:09:03,389 --> 01:09:06,267
- No, I'd rather wait until after the show.
- Now that I know...

890
01:09:06,429 --> 01:09:08,784
No. I'll tell you later.
Come on. Let's go.

891
01:09:08,949 --> 01:09:10,667
That's it, isn't it?

892
01:09:11,709 --> 01:09:15,941
I'm gonna feel awful about this.
You shouldn't have done that.

893
01:09:16,109 --> 01:09:17,144
No.

894
01:09:17,309 --> 01:09:20,460
Especially since
it's for "dear, sweet Sonya."

895
01:09:20,669 --> 01:09:22,261
What is?

896
01:09:22,549 --> 01:09:25,507
I can see why you wanted
to save the surprise.

897
01:09:26,069 --> 01:09:29,300
- Holy smoke! Something's happened here.
- So it seems.

898
01:09:29,469 --> 01:09:32,347
- But I bought this bracelet from Martin...
- Certainly.

899
01:09:32,509 --> 01:09:35,899
And after he sold it, he went
to all that trouble, just for the fun of it.

900
01:09:36,069 --> 01:09:37,866
You know Martin's apt to do anything.

901
01:09:38,029 --> 01:09:41,863
"One woman in 50 million" can
certainly be simple-minded at times.

902
01:09:42,989 --> 01:09:45,025
There's a perfect explanation.

903
01:09:45,189 --> 01:09:48,420
Write it to me. A letter will reach me
in Panama in about a week.

904
01:09:48,589 --> 01:09:50,898
What's Panama got to do with this?

905
01:09:51,069 --> 01:09:53,344
I'll be there with Capt. Barton.

906
01:09:53,509 --> 01:09:56,262
We're leaving in a few days,
right after the marriage.

907
01:09:56,429 --> 01:09:59,307
- You've got this all wrong.
- The guards.

908
01:10:33,509 --> 01:10:38,981
Would you please get me
Mrs. Martin Cortland, Adirondack 5636.

909
01:10:39,149 --> 01:10:40,423
Thank you. I'll hold on.

910
01:10:43,029 --> 01:10:46,339
- See you at rehearsal.
- Sure thing, baby. You said it.

911
01:10:46,509 --> 01:10:49,182
Now, that's sensible.
Martin will be very happy.

912
01:10:49,349 --> 01:10:52,944
Oh, he'll be tickled pink.
Everybody will be happy.

913
01:10:53,109 --> 01:10:54,906
- Goodbye.
- Goodbye.

914
01:11:00,109 --> 01:11:03,579
Hello? Hello? Julia?

915
01:11:03,829 --> 01:11:05,308
This is Robert.

916
01:11:05,669 --> 01:11:09,867
Yeah. Julia, Martin and I
are putting on a show at camp.

917
01:11:11,349 --> 01:11:14,182
Well, hello, boys.
I've been looking for you. Sit down.

918
01:11:14,349 --> 01:11:20,060
Julia, what I called to say is,
it looks like very stormy weather up here.

919
01:11:20,229 --> 01:11:21,821
Do tell.

920
01:11:23,309 --> 01:11:26,142
It's a tornado, honey. A hurricane.

921
01:11:26,309 --> 01:11:29,267
In fact, the blow is so hard,
it lifts you right off your feet.

922
01:11:29,429 --> 01:11:31,465
Goodbye. I have to go now.

923
01:11:31,629 --> 01:11:33,540
To the guardhouse, boys.

924
01:11:40,109 --> 01:11:42,179
Sonya's gonna be very good
in this show.

925
01:11:42,349 --> 01:11:45,147
- I don't think we'll miss Sheila at all.
- I don't think so.

926
01:11:45,309 --> 01:11:47,982
Is she really going off to Panama
with that Barton fella?

927
01:11:48,149 --> 01:11:49,707
So I've heard.

928
01:11:49,869 --> 01:11:53,100
Too bad. It's your own fault.
You will play around.

929
01:11:53,269 --> 01:11:55,100
I'm just a dirty dog.

930
01:11:55,269 --> 01:11:57,339
Live and learn, I always say.

931
01:11:58,829 --> 01:12:00,547
Live and learn.

932
01:12:01,629 --> 01:12:06,305
Robert, do me a favour, will you?
Look back and tell me, is that Julia?

933
01:12:06,469 --> 01:12:08,699
I wouldn't be surprised.

934
01:12:08,869 --> 01:12:12,225
Did you have anything to do with this,
you despicable, sordid...?

935
01:12:12,789 --> 01:12:16,782
- Julia, why, this is a delightful surprise!
- Hello, Martin dear.

936
01:12:16,949 --> 01:12:18,462
- Hello, Robert.
- Hello, Julia.

937
01:12:18,629 --> 01:12:20,585
You'd think you'd telegraph
and warn a person.

938
01:12:20,749 --> 01:12:22,819
Not that I'm not tickled to death
to see you.

939
01:12:22,989 --> 01:12:25,742
- You look delirious.
- He's missed you terribly, Julia.

940
01:12:25,909 --> 01:12:29,185
He's been pining his heart away. He
rushed into town to buy you something.

941
01:12:29,349 --> 01:12:32,182
A lovely little trinket,
right there in his pocket.

942
01:12:33,109 --> 01:12:36,021
Something to scratch with, no doubt.

943
01:12:36,389 --> 01:12:37,981
Well...

944
01:12:40,469 --> 01:12:43,267
"For my dear, sweet Sonya."

945
01:12:43,429 --> 01:12:45,784
Listen, Julia,
there's been a hideous mistake.

946
01:12:45,949 --> 01:12:48,179
Oh, Sonya, would you
come here a moment, please?

947
01:12:48,349 --> 01:12:51,466
- I can explain everything.
- Better make it a good one.

948
01:12:51,629 --> 01:12:54,302
It's Robert. I'm using his apartment
and last night, he said:

949
01:12:54,469 --> 01:12:57,905
"Martin, bring me the bracelet
I bought for Sonya."

950
01:12:58,069 --> 01:13:00,503
Look at it. It's the same one
he bought for Sheila.

951
01:13:00,669 --> 01:13:03,979
He broke Sheila's heart playing around
with Sonya, and she gave it back.

952
01:13:04,149 --> 01:13:08,427
And then the cad had the name changed
on the very same bracelet.

953
01:13:08,589 --> 01:13:09,817
Boy, that was a pip.

954
01:13:09,989 --> 01:13:11,786
Take back your filthy bauble, sir.

955
01:13:11,949 --> 01:13:15,305
And in the future, do not make me
a party to your low intrigues.

956
01:13:15,469 --> 01:13:18,859
- Yes, Mr. Curtis.
- This little present is for you, Sonya.

957
01:13:19,029 --> 01:13:22,021
Oh, how wonderful!

958
01:13:25,389 --> 01:13:28,222
"For my dear, sweet Sonya."

959
01:13:28,389 --> 01:13:31,142
- Oh, Martin! I love you, darling!
- Stop it! Stop it!

960
01:13:31,309 --> 01:13:34,824
- What is the meaning of this?
- Sonya, this is Mrs. Cortland.

961
01:13:36,269 --> 01:13:39,227
- Mrs. Cortland?
- Yes, my wife.

962
01:13:39,549 --> 01:13:41,187
The woman I treasure.

963
01:13:41,349 --> 01:13:45,103
Sonya, didn't you say something
about having possibly to leave the show?

964
01:13:45,269 --> 01:13:49,979
Why, yes. There's my sick uncle
and my sick cousin and...

965
01:13:50,149 --> 01:13:54,222
- And something might happen to you too.
- Yes.

966
01:13:54,389 --> 01:13:58,223
Well, I'm happy to have met you,
Mrs. Cortland.

967
01:14:01,869 --> 01:14:03,939
There goes your gal.

968
01:14:04,829 --> 01:14:06,660
Boys, back to the guardhouse.
Let's go.

969
01:14:06,829 --> 01:14:08,547
What do you mean?
What about the show?

970
01:14:08,709 --> 01:14:10,939
Show? Without a leading lady?
Ready, boys?

971
01:14:11,109 --> 01:14:12,861
Wait! There's Sheila. Get her back.

972
01:14:13,029 --> 01:14:15,179
She's going to Panama. However...

973
01:14:15,349 --> 01:14:20,662
...if you tried explaining what happened in
my apartment with "dear, sweet Sonya"...

974
01:14:22,709 --> 01:14:25,587
- I don't know what you're talking about.
- That's what I thought.

975
01:14:25,749 --> 01:14:29,788
Boys, it's my right to serve my sentence.
Take me back to the guardhouse.

976
01:14:29,949 --> 01:14:32,099
- Okay, soldier, let's go.
- Robert, my...

977
01:14:32,269 --> 01:14:34,100
Now, Martin, my pet...

978
01:14:34,269 --> 01:14:37,784
...l'm going to get to the bottom
of this Sonya matter if it's the last...

979
01:14:37,949 --> 01:14:44,184
Julia, I'm as innocent as a newborn babe,
or a little older, perhaps.

980
01:14:46,989 --> 01:14:49,901
Hey, Kewpie, Swivel Tongue,
where do you think I'm going?

981
01:14:50,069 --> 01:14:51,661
- Again?
- What happened?

982
01:14:51,829 --> 01:14:54,980
- Oh, nothing. Show's off, that's all.
- Off? How come?

983
01:14:55,149 --> 01:14:57,379
Miss Winthrop decided
to go to Panama instead.

984
01:14:57,549 --> 01:15:00,825
Now, I ask you,
disappointing all those poor soldiers...

985
01:15:00,989 --> 01:15:03,549
...is that fair of Miss Winthrop?
- It's a crime.

986
01:15:03,709 --> 01:15:06,746
That's what I think. Understand?

987
01:15:11,269 --> 01:15:13,146
Do you understand?

988
01:15:15,589 --> 01:15:17,147
Well, what are we waiting on?

989
01:15:17,469 --> 01:15:19,858
So you see,
she walks right out on the show.

990
01:15:20,029 --> 01:15:22,827
Yeah. They promised us a big shindig,
and it's off!

991
01:15:22,989 --> 01:15:25,662
- How do you like that?
- How did she get that way?

992
01:15:25,829 --> 01:15:27,820
These two fellas tell me
there's no show.

993
01:15:27,989 --> 01:15:29,581
What are we, soldiers or mice?

994
01:15:29,749 --> 01:15:33,378
- This Winthrop gal picks up and walks.
- What's the idea? She can't do that.

995
01:15:33,549 --> 01:15:36,586
I'm sorry, but if Uncle Sam
were to walk in here and ask me...

996
01:15:36,749 --> 01:15:38,467
...to go back into that show, I'd...

997
01:15:38,629 --> 01:15:41,268
We're all packed and ready to leave
on our honeymoon, sir.

998
01:15:41,429 --> 01:15:43,420
What's so important about a honeymoon?

999
01:15:43,589 --> 01:15:47,138
When you've been married 25 years,
as I have, you'll look back and wonder...

1000
01:15:47,309 --> 01:15:48,867
But never mind that.

1001
01:15:49,029 --> 01:15:52,146
One more word from you,
and I'll be forced to have you disciplined.

1002
01:15:52,309 --> 01:15:53,742
Yes, sir. Sorry, sir.

1003
01:15:53,909 --> 01:15:58,300
Now, here's a problem for that charming
Captain Curtis to handle.

1004
01:15:58,469 --> 01:16:00,744
I have a funny hunch
he's working on it.

1005
01:16:00,909 --> 01:16:03,503
- Miss Winthrop...
- You're wasting time, colonel.

1006
01:16:08,109 --> 01:16:11,181
You hear that? The whole
blooming Army is calling for you.

1007
01:16:11,349 --> 01:16:14,659
And I might say, that includes myself.

1008
01:16:18,629 --> 01:16:21,143
- Sheila's changed her mind.
- The show's on!

1009
01:16:21,309 --> 01:16:24,346
- Well, what a pleasant surprise.
- Come on, let's get going.

1010
01:16:24,509 --> 01:16:28,024
Yes, sir, just one second.
I got a little business about the show.

1011
01:16:29,589 --> 01:16:32,501
I put a big military wedding number
in this show for a purpose.

1012
01:16:32,669 --> 01:16:35,820
With Sheila and I
as bride and groom, see?

1013
01:16:35,989 --> 01:16:38,378
What I had in mind was...

1014
01:16:38,549 --> 01:16:42,747
...suppose you fellas got a real justice
of the peace to play that part?

1015
01:16:42,909 --> 01:16:45,821
That would save Miss Winthrop
that little trip to Panama.

1016
01:16:45,989 --> 01:16:47,422
See what I mean?

1017
01:16:48,189 --> 01:16:49,668
- Yeah.
- Sure.

1018
01:16:49,829 --> 01:16:53,185
All right. Get to work, and no slip-ups.
See you in the auditorium.

1019
01:16:53,349 --> 01:16:55,783
All right, kids. Let's go.

1020
01:17:03,069 --> 01:17:05,264
- Yes?
- It's going fine, don't you think?

1021
01:17:05,429 --> 01:17:08,262
One more number and it's over,
and that'll be even finer.

1022
01:17:08,429 --> 01:17:11,421
You're going to be the loveliest bride
anybody ever saw.

1023
01:17:11,629 --> 01:17:14,189
If you recall, the Army said,
"Just dance with him.

1024
01:17:14,349 --> 01:17:16,340
You don't have to talk to him."

1025
01:17:23,389 --> 01:17:28,747
Oh, here comes the bride, no less
It's hot stuff, that fluffy dress

1026
01:17:28,869 --> 01:17:33,659
I must admit, though she's lit
She looks a bit sweet

1027
01:17:34,029 --> 01:17:38,819
No wonder her Romeo
Begins shouting hi-de- ho

1028
01:17:38,949 --> 01:17:43,500
As his bride starts to stride
To a boogie beat

1029
01:17:44,549 --> 01:17:48,701
There's a big increase in marriages
Due to a tune, they say

1030
01:17:48,829 --> 01:17:54,745
The wedding cak e walk
Is the roundelay

1031
01:17:54,869 --> 01:17:59,624
When newlyweds in fancy carriages
Leave the reception gay

1032
01:17:59,749 --> 01:18:05,779
The wedding cak e walk
Sends them on their way

1033
01:18:05,909 --> 01:18:11,267
Pasty choirs in tasty churches
Give it all they got

1034
01:18:11,389 --> 01:18:16,668
Prudish old preachers on their perches
Say, "Amen, it's hot"

1035
01:18:16,789 --> 01:18:21,226
All those bridal suites at Claridge's
Have radios that play

1036
01:18:21,349 --> 01:18:26,548
The wedding cak e walk
Night and day

1037
01:19:24,989 --> 01:19:30,063
If any person can show cause why
they may not lawfully be joined together...

1038
01:19:30,229 --> 01:19:33,983
...let him now speak,
or forever hold his peace.

1039
01:19:34,189 --> 01:19:36,828
Do you take this woman
to be your lawful wedded wife?

1040
01:19:37,429 --> 01:19:38,942
I do.

1041
01:19:39,189 --> 01:19:41,703
Do you take this man
to be your lawful wedded husband?

1042
01:19:41,869 --> 01:19:42,904
I do.

1043
01:19:43,069 --> 01:19:48,348
In accordance with the authority vested
in me, I now pronounce you man and wife.

1044
01:22:19,869 --> 01:22:21,666
Will you stop,
the show is over.

1045
01:22:21,829 --> 01:22:24,263
The real show has just started,
Mrs. Curtis.

1046
01:22:24,429 --> 01:22:25,942
Mrs. What?

1047
01:22:26,109 --> 01:22:30,068
Ladies and gentlemen... Just in time,
Capt. Barton and my dear friend, Martin.

1048
01:22:30,229 --> 01:22:33,062
Listen, everybody,
Sheila and I are man and wife.

1049
01:22:33,229 --> 01:22:37,700
Yes, the man who performed the wedding
ceremony was a real justice of the peace.

1050
01:22:37,869 --> 01:22:41,179
You are, without a doubt, the...
Let go of me.

1051
01:22:41,509 --> 01:22:45,502
I believe Curtis was to be returned
to the guardhouse right after the show.

1052
01:22:45,669 --> 01:22:46,758
Come on, Curtis.

1053
01:22:50,509 --> 01:22:52,306
I'll have this annulled,
then have him arrested.

1054
01:22:52,469 --> 01:22:55,779
Think it over, darling.
A husband in jail is no use at all.

1055
01:22:58,029 --> 01:23:00,668
- You and your show!
- Listen, now that you're married...

1056
01:23:00,829 --> 01:23:02,979
...I can't let Robert
be tortured like this...

1057
01:23:03,149 --> 01:23:05,868
...so I've got to tell you,
I changed the name on the bracelet.

1058
01:23:06,029 --> 01:23:10,864
I framed the thing up in his apartment,
so that I could get Sonya into the show.

1059
01:23:11,029 --> 01:23:13,987
I'd have told you this before,
but that old G-woman of mine...

1060
01:23:14,149 --> 01:23:16,424
Oh, you darling!

1061
01:23:17,269 --> 01:23:19,737
I wonder if they have daylight saving
around here?

1062
01:23:26,229 --> 01:23:28,584
Hurry up, Swivel.
Curtis has to have a honeymoon.

1063
01:23:28,749 --> 01:23:30,944
He should've started digging
from the guardhouse.

1064
01:23:31,069 --> 01:23:32,866
Oh, shut up and dig.

1065
01:23:38,149 --> 01:23:40,105
Mrs. Curtis calling on her husband.

1066
01:23:40,269 --> 01:23:42,829
The last I heard, the Curtises
don't live here anymore.

1067
01:23:42,989 --> 01:23:45,184
They broke up, I heard.

1068
01:23:45,469 --> 01:23:47,346
I heard she might be
coming back to him.

1069
01:23:48,149 --> 01:23:49,901
You did?

1070
01:23:50,109 --> 01:23:52,703
But it's rather awkward
with the bridegroom behind bars.

1071
01:23:52,869 --> 01:23:54,507
Awkward? It's awful.

1072
01:23:54,869 --> 01:23:57,747
I could pitch a tent out here,
and we could look at each other.

1073
01:23:57,909 --> 01:23:59,422
Curtis.

1074
01:24:01,469 --> 01:24:05,223
On recommendation of Captain Barton,
I'm releasing you for your honeymoon.

1075
01:24:05,389 --> 01:24:07,061
Colonel, you're a sweetheart.

1076
01:24:07,229 --> 01:24:11,222
Oh, sorry, sir. Yes, sir.
Thank you, sir. Yes, sir. Thank you.

1077
01:24:16,909 --> 01:24:19,548
Curtis? Curtis?

1078
01:24:24,869 --> 01:24:27,099
I guess we're lost.
It's pretty foggy tonight.

1079
01:24:27,269 --> 01:24:29,464
Yes. You see, we had a date with...

1080
01:24:29,629 --> 01:24:33,099
we're going to China...

